            <figcaption class="mt-2 px-6 sm:px-0 font-mono text-[0.68rem] text-ink-faint">Consistent closure application across high-volume production. Photo: Pexels</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <div class="space-y-4 text-[0.95rem] text-ink-light">
            <p>A capping chuck is the torque-transmitting interface between a capping turret spindle and the closure. It sits at the bottom of each spindle station on a rotary capper, or on the descending head of an inline unit. The chuck grips the closure's outer shell, applies controlled rotational torque, and threads the cap onto the container finish to a target removal-torque spec.</p>

            <p>Torque consistency depends on the chuck's internal drive mechanism (magnetic hysteresis, friction clutch, pneumatic cylinder, or servo). Getting this right is what separates a line that runs at 2% CV from one that dumps product. A properly calibrated chuck delivers full thread engagement, correct TE band bridge fracture, and enough seal compression to hold headspace vacuum without leaking.</p>

            <p>The chuck bore is precision-machined or molded to match the closure's outer geometry: knurl pattern, anti-rotation ribs, pilfer-band skirt. On ROPP lines, the headset assembly also carries a top-pressure pad and threading rollers that plastically deform the aluminum shell onto the bottle finish helix. Regardless of type, the chuck interfaces with the spindle through a keyed, splined, or bayonet coupling. Any backlash here shows up as torque scatter.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="spec-panel mt-8">
